voice_to_text: So the video that I posted about getting a bad grade got a lot of people talking in the comment section. I've also seen a lot of stitches on this. In support of setting standards for your kids, why don't we get ready together? Well, I talk about our strict rules. Number one, my kids need to read at least 30 minutes a day, even on the weekends. We have seen that kids simply cannot read. Seventh graders are reading at a third grade level, and high schoolers are reading at a sixth grade level every single day. That is a must. Number two is no phones allowed in your bedroom. This only really applies to my oldest, but if you need to make a phone call, you can do that downstairs in another room. I do not want your phone in your room. So we do no screen time Monday through Thursday. So no phone unless you need to call a friend. And no TV. Kids are so busy with homework, after school activities, dinner anyway, that there's really no time. Obviously in the summer that changes. And when they do get screen time, we do set limits on that as well. Hour on the phone maximum. Of course, TV is a little over two hours if they're watching a movie. Do not allow our kids to use their phones or ipads at restaurants at all. This was a really hard one to let go of when we did Allow our kids to bring devices into restaurants. They displayed zombie like behaviours. Screen time free for over two years. And it has made such a big difference. And actually have conversations. We can laugh, we can talk. And I wanna make it very clear that this doesn't apply for every kid, but this is what worked for us. And the last strict rule for us. While it might be controversial, you are absolutely hundred percent expected to do well in school. And if they are struggling, we will absolutely help them with what they need to succeed. Of course, every kid is different, and I'm sure there are challenges along the way. But we know that our kids are very capable of doing well in school. And this is what works for us. A lonely tortoise turned to online dating to find a girlfriend after previously attempting to start a relationship with a rock. 🪨 Thanks to tortoise tinder, he met Estrella, and the couple moved in together after carrying on a long-distance relationship via video calls first. 🐢  Hugo and Estrella live at the Australian Reptile Park and they post regular updates about their animals! ❤️  See more from the couple: @AustReptilePark  📸 Australian Reptile Park  #tortoise #galapagostortoise #relationshipgoals #animalcouple #relationships #couplethings #wildlife #reptiles
voice_to_text: A lonely tortoise who previously had a rock for a girlfriend finally turned to online dating and started a long distance relationship with an actual tortoise. Now that they're together in person, their relationship has been thriving. Hugo, the Galapagos tortoise, spent seven decades without ever having a girlfriend. He's lived at the Australian Reptile Park since 1963 when he was brought there as an ambassador for his endangered species, and while he's very well cared for, over the years he started showing more signs of being lonely, including trying to start a relationship with a goose named Lenny and then trying to start one with a shell shaped rock in his habitat, neither of which worked out. But finding him a girlfriend wasn't an easy task. These species is protected and there are more restrictions than there were in the 60s, so it's not exactly easy to just acquire a Galapagos tortoise anymore. The reptile park created a tinder profile for him and ran a paid post on social media showcasing his profile to see if any other sanctuaries might have a lonely female tortoise of their own. They were in luck because a zoo in Germany came forward with a potential match, a 21 year old Galapagos tortoise named Estrella. Hugo swiped right on Estrella because she needed to be quarantined before she could move to Australia to be with him. They started a long distance relationship with regular video call dates while they waited. And when they Finally met in person. The spark was there. Meaning there's a possibility of Galapa babies in the future.

voice_to_text: this is one of the most painful conditions any person can have it is called a polynatyl abscess and it is formed because of an infection in these polynatyl sinuses which is a passageway between the coxas or the tail bone in your skin and what happens is that often we see this in individuals who are overweight males those who are sitting for a period long periods of time but we could also see it in women and what happens is you have an ingrown hair that gets stuck in these sinuses and eventually over time become infected causing fluid to accumulated causing an infection called an abscess in the way that we manage this is by surgery so often times we perform surgery to get rid of these infection they are seeing how they perform the surgery so the way they do it is they essentially form an incision on that passageway and surgeons are able to get rid of these ingrown hair because the key is to remove the ingrown hair so that doesn't accumulate and cause infection and then they also laser this passageway to form scar tissue so the sinuses are closed so that this infection doesn't reoccur again so what's important here is that if you fit that demographic of a male overweight who sits for prolonged periods of time and you're having tailbone pain make sure you talk to a primary care provider to make sure you don't have a pile of metal abscess because those could be life threatening

video_description: this is from the perspective of an independent unsigned solo artist who would need to hire session musicians to form a band. the winner doesn't only have to pay for travel and accommodation for themselves and their band, but they would also need to pay the musicians they hire - unless they're lucky enough to not have to pay them as sometimes musicians will agree to do these things for free, for example if they're your friend. all of these plus various unexpected costs that pop up. this whole 'play for exposure and do it for free' really contributes to the exploitation of artists - it's not fair, we need to start getting paid for our time and efforts, and stop going to these awful promoters for gigs and opportunities. sure I love what I do I love singing on stage and writing songs etc but I'm reaching a point where I understand what I'm worth and I'm less willing to entertain things like this. and lots of other artists are as well and I'm here for it. dont get me wrong there are some instances where I would gig for free but in those instances I would get compensation/value from something else, whether that's free food and drink or the opportunity to work with some really influential people. #livemusic #promoters #newmusic #singing #independentartist

So we went to, like, Mount Washington, for those of you don't know, it's like a really nice lookout over Pittsburgh. And there was a place near our school, and it was called the fountain of youth. It was essentially just like a well that people in the town used to go to when it was in use. So we went there. It was night time. It wasn't like midnight. It was like nine or so. It wasn't super late. Um, we went there, and the way that this well was set up, it was, like, carved. There was a piece carved out of a rock formation, and then you'd walk in and then get water out of the well inside of it. So the. The girls inside, one of them said, hey, I can kind of hear, like, rocks moving around in here. It sounds like there's something else in here. This is coming from someone who sat on the executive board, with the CEO, with the C O O, with all of the higher UPS. They don't care. They don't care what you have going outside of work. It is about the result. It is about the deliverable. And the sooner you remove the emotion out of the work that you do, the further that you can go. Because when you start to think that they care if you had a bad day, then you give yourself an excuse to have a bad day. When you think that they hear that you're doing really well in your personal life, you give yourself an excuse. When you remove the emotion, you will go further. Show up, be passionate about the work that you were doing. If you are. If you don't care about the work you're doing, do the bare minimum, but take the emotion out of it. video_description: If we were the emotional regulator within our family structure, it’s likely that we not only had to tolerate poor behavior, but soothe and balance the person giving it.  This can lead us to be deeply perceptive, and really see past the outward actions and into the inner workings of where they’re coming from.  It’s a form of compassion that formed out of necessity.  It helped us diffuse a volatile situation.  It helped survive.  But this can become a pattern that we unconsciously copy and paste onto various situations throughout the rest of our lives — relationships, friendships, work dynamics…. Situations where we actually have the autonomy to stand up for ourselves, and prioritize our own energy.  While that doesn’t necessarily mean the pattern will change overnight, it’s just an invitation to notice.  Where are you repeating this pattern, where it’s not totally needed? And how can you practice having compassion, AND boundaries? How can you maintain awareness and understanding, AND your own energy supply? Be patient. Stay open. Stay curious.  Notice how it feels 🤍 #traumahealing #healingjourney #healthyboundaries

voice_to_text: There are certain things that your employer cannot do. My name is Craig Levey and I'm an employment law attorney and here are three examples. First, your employer cannot prevent you from discussing your wages with your coworkers. The National Labor Relations Act, or NLRA, is a federal law that states that employees are allowed to discuss their wages with their coworkers, and companies cannot retaliate against employees for doing so. So if you are an employee that is covered by that law and your company has a policy that states you cannot discuss your wages with your coworkers, that is unenforceable. Second, your employer cannot terminate your employment because you complained about something illegal going on at work. For example, many employees complain about sexual harassment or discrimination at work and are retaliated against because of that. There's a federal law to protect you in that case, and also many state laws. Also, there are federal and state whistleblower laws which protect individuals if they make certain complaints that categorize them as a whistleblower. And third, your employer cannot terminate your employment because you make an OSHA complaint stating that they aren't in compliance with certain health and safety standards. Far too often I see employees make complaints with OSHA and the company responds by retaliating, often terminating the employees employment.

video_description: Like it or lump it, we're in a recession and tattooing is a luxury industry, I'm seeing a lot of excuses and very few solutions being posted online. Q. What should artists be doing to ensure they survive this recession? #tattooartist #digbeth #birmingham
voice_to_text: Is this the end for tattooing? It's no secret that right now the tattoo industry is in a bad state. Artists nationally are struggling to fill their books, and when they do, they're littered with last minute cancellation. But why? Some artists have made videos claiming that it's social media suppression. Some have ranted saying that it's an over saturated market with too many tattoo artists and tattoo shops. I don't think it's either. So what can we do? Will lowering day rates and offering deals remedy this situation? Will changing the dated, industry wide outlook on how we use social media be the solution? Or do some artists need to swallow their ego and start doing small tattoos again for a much more affordable price to make sure they make ends meet? This isn't the first recession the tattoo industry is faced and it won't be the last. We have to adapt and overcome to get through this together. But the question is how? If you've agreed with what I've said or you've disagreed with what I've said, let me know in the comments. Thanks for watching. Have a sick day.

voice_to_text: I was out of town for a few days, and I got home late last night, and when I saw my boys this morning, the first thing they asked for were strawberry scones with a lemon drizzle. I can't believe I actually grew these here. So I grabbed those and then got some milk and eggs for my chickens, and I diced up my strawberries, added those to my bowl, added a bit of lemon zest. Did you guys know I'm proficient at juggling? Added my chicken, milk and egg eggs. Really combined everything. Then formed it into a little disc on some Parchment paper before cutting it into eight little triangles, added a bit of egg wash for some shine, and got started on my glaze, which was just powdered sugar, lemon juice, and some homemade vanilla extract. I personally love a dollop of whipped cream on a scone. Whipped cream on anything is good. So I whipped up some of that by hand. I'm gonna be honest and let you in on a secret I used to be scared of Black folks and yes this also means there was a lot of anti Blackness and racism that I've had to unpack in my life over the past 30 something years and I'm gonna start out with some background not as an excuse for why I felt that way for a long time but as context so I grew up in Alabama in a time where there wasn't that much diversity in the state even less than there is now and in my elementary school it was maybe like a couple Asians and a couple Black students on my third day of kindergarten I was cornered in the bathroom by a fellow student who was Black  and she beat me up to this day I don't know why she did what she did but it doesn't really matter at the end of the day it happened and it influenced how I felt about Black people for a long time not to mention my family being Korean I grew up with a lot of harmful stereotypes about Black folks that they are good at dancing and sports and it was mostly because my family didn't know that many Black folks so these preconceived notions were all from media and things that we had seen otherwise on TV when this changed was when I entered college and yeah that was a long time to hold those views but that fear was also what kept me back from becoming closer to anyone who was Black  beyond a mere acquaintance I went to a PWI and it wasn't that much different from how I had grown up I grew up around mostly white communities and when I went to this PWI it was a sudden culture shock not because it was a largely white private little arts college but because there was suddenly a huge class divide as well in the communities of my K through 12 education most people were around the same similar income bracket even though I was always on the lower end of the scale but when I went to college and they happened to room me with one of the like other 10 Korean students I couldn't relate to my roommate at all and it's ironic because I live in California now but that's where my roommate was from and she was so different from me not just income bracket wise but I could not relate to this fellow Korean student despite what the college wanted me to do and what ended up happening was I made friends with my roommate's  college classmate for one of their classes together and Sam came over and we became really really good friends in fact Sam was my first really best friend in life and she taught me a lot and we're still in touch today we're still really really good friends today but it single handedly changed how I felt and single handedly taught me so much of what I thought was true ended up being wrong and the thing about our friendship was I don't realize we had so many commonalities because Sam is Haitian American and we ended up bonding a lot over cultural similarities and parental relationships and we would watch both western dramas like Grey's Anatomy every Thursday night and also Korean dramas and we would eat together and I went over to her house and all of these things so Sam was like my first step into decolonizing and unlearning anti Blackness and racism I also had an RA - residential adviser and his name was Petey and again like Sam Petey and I are now going on like almost 20 years of friendship because we're old and Petey was step two into unlearning all of the harmful things I had learned in my childhood and young adulthood even it's funny because you know those two friends who share one brain cell that they ping pong between each other that is basically my friendship with Petey we are not- somehow if you put us together we are intelligent individuals, separately but put together we have made some of the stupidest decisions have come up with the stupidest scenarios to be in to this day that we talk about both back when we were in school and as adults and I'm really quite thankful to those two in particular but even after that after I graduated from college and I became friends with quite a diverse group of friends and people and I think it's also partly because I'm autistic it's hard for me to relate to different people in the world and it's much easier for me to be apathetic about things which is also why my handle is goodbye apathy to remind myself that apathy is not a good thing and that yes you can be introverted but friends are the community that teach you that there is a much larger world out there and that your worldviews may be absolutely incorrect especially if you grew up with bias and inherited stereotypes and all these things drilled into you and I'm also gonna be honest and say I probably wouldn't care that much about Falasteen if I hadn't known a classmate from Falasteen also when I was in elementary school and I remember her because she was one of the very few like very very few people who was incredibly nice to me and didn't make me feel foreign and other I spoke with her recently and she sent a picture of her birthday party that I forgot I had attended but once she sent that picture I remember distinctly that no one else had invited me to their birthday party until she did and it sticks out to me as a memory that I forgot until she saw the picture and while my friend is safe while all of my friends are safe for now it's why I care about Falasteen it's why I post about anti Blackness within both the East Asian community and specifically the Korean community because it affects my friends and if that makes me selfish if that makes me weird that's fine this is how I relate to the world through my friends who I know what I've learned through my friends and I especially remember one incident from college that truly cemented how Petey and Sam go through the world and it's one Petey and I went to the library together it was late at night it was kind of chilly so Petey was in a hoodie and he had the school lanyard with his school ID around his neck and the white librarian stopped him and stopped him only and said I'm gonna need a secondary form of ID and I remember just pausing in shock like why are you asking he when he is clearly a student here and she said oh you know that lanyard could be faked it could be yours meaning me and I was like no no no no no I think I think something's wrong here I think what you're doing is very racist why would you assume that only me is the legit student when we both have backpacks we both have hoodies on we both have lanyards what is the difference between him and I our race and ethnicity and that taught me so much without Petry having to say a single word just seeing one moment in his life and it sticks with me now nearly 20 years later that this is reality for a lot of different people that I didn't give a shit about until we became friends so there's no moral of the story there's just- sharing my journey from where I began to where I'm at now and I continue to unpack things year by year I'm not done by any means but I wanted to share that because that to me means a lot more than sharing some historical figure for Black History Month that I don't know too much about this is what I know and this is what I've experienced okay bye

video_description: Whats the closest you’ve come to dying? #reddit #redditstories #redditreadings #reddit_tiktok #fyp #redditstorytime #seekhelp #minecraft
voice_to_text: Closest you've ever come to dying. On April 21st of 2017, I was in my neighborhood knocking on doors and introducing myself to the neighbors. I was 1/1 year Realtor trying to get my business going. Toward the end of a 4 hour day of door knocking, I approached the door and rang the bell. Almost immediately I felt nauseous and knew I was about to pass out. I wake up to the sound of a lady speaking to 911. She was spelling my name to the 911 operator. I always wear my name badge when out. As I came to, she asked if I wanted an ambulance. I said no, I'm just dehydrated. The lovely lady was a retired nurse in her late 60s or early 70s. She had her husband drive me the 3 blocks back home. I began drinking water but passed out a couple of more times. I called my girlfriend and asked her to come over as soon as she got off work. Not wanting to fall down again, I went to my bedroom and laid down. She arrived with Gatorade and I drank part of one before throwing it back up. I passed out a few more times. I live with my older sister who was returning from a business trip that evening. When she got home, I spoke with her about passing out multiple times. That afternoon. My sister insisted that we go to the ER. We all piled into my truck and My sister drove. I passed out again during the drive to the hospital. The ER nurse got me on a table after checking me in. By this point, I was feeling very hungry, having missed lunch, and it was now well after 10 p m. I explained to the staff that I had passed out at least 10 to 12 times today. The medical staff went into the hall to discuss my case. Impossible treatment. I felt the nausea again and told my sister it was starting again. She had not witnessed me passing out yet. She ran to the door and called the medical staff. When she turned around, my heart had flatlined. The ER staff immediately performed CPR, including shocking me with the defibrillator. When I came to, I looked at the nurse and said, it happened again, right? She asked if this is what I had been experiencing all afternoon. I confirmed it before passing out yet again. The episodes continued for the next several hours. When they finally got me awake again, the cardiologist explained that I wasn't passing out. I was actually going into cardiac arrest each time due to an issue with my vagus nerve. They decided that the best course of action would be a pacemaker. I can only imagine the pain and fear that my family went through that evening. My part was pretty easy. Heart stops, pass out, CPR and wait back up. The one benefit of dying more than 30 Times in one day is that I now have a much greater appreciation for life
